"{\"uid\": \"citizen.co.za-sport-luxolo-adams-not-in-shape-paris-olympics\", \"text\": \"Home\\u00bbSport  ByWesley Botton  Chief sports journalist  3 minute read  17 July 2024  05:10 pm  Luxolo Adams in action during last year's World Athletics Championships in Budapest. Picture: Anton Geyser/Gallo Images  Now that he's run twice over the last couple of weeks, it is clear that Luxolo Adams should not go to the Olympics.  The removal of the 27-year-old sprinter from the SA team for the Paris Games has not only caused controversy but haslanded up in court.  Adams, however, should not be selected ahead ofWayde van Niekerkfor the\\u00a0200m event\\u00a0in the French capital.  That's not to say Adams does not have a legal case. He was initially included in the team, and then removed, and Athletics South Africa's qualifying criteria does not seem to give the federation much leeway to select athletes based on form.  But picking Adams would be a mistake because he's not in shape.  While he has apparently recovered from a hamstring injury that derailed the first half of his 2024 campaign, in his only two 200m races this year, Adams clocked 21.50 in Italy earlier this month and 21.31 in Switzerland on Tuesday.  To put this into perspective, his season's bestranks him 67th in South Africain the 200m sprint, and the country has 19 junior athletes (including two 15-year-old sprinters) who have run quicker than him this year.  The reality is that five South African athletes have achieved the qualifying criteria in the 200m event, and only three can go to Paris.  In a scenario like this, where two athletes are going to miss out, it makes sense for ASA to pick the three athletes who are in the best shape, which is what they have done by selecting Shaun Maswanganyi,Benjamin Richardsonand Van Niekerk (ahead of Adams and Sinesipho Dambile).  If Adams wins his court case, and ASA is forced to select him, it means Van Niekerk will be dropped from the squad and will not be able to compete in the 4x100m or 4x400m relays, which puts a dent in the nation's medal hopes.  It must bedisappointing for Adamsto have lost his spot, but he needs to admit that he's not fit enough to represent his country right now and should focus on regaining his form, rather than forcing ASA to spend money on legal costs to\\u00a0fight the matter in court.  The federation has made the right decision.  Add The Citizen as a Preferred Source on Google and follow us on Google News to see more of our trusted reporting in Google News and Top Stories.  Download our app  Get the latest news and updates on Whatsapp  The latest news directly in your inbox  Support Local Journalism  2026 The Citizen. All Rights Reserved.\"}"